Can significantly reduce the latency for ops like mean and variance, but also increase latency for small reduction ops such as sum, max, etc. However these small ops are fast anyway. So I think it's worth to parallelize the reduction by default.

Will add some benchmark result soon...

@anijain2305 @Huyuwei @kevinthesun

Right now relay vm dont support any/symbolic shape with dense, because dense schedule/compute require input shape known as constant beforehand.

This PR add polymorphic inline JIT, so if a function cannot be lowered at compile time, for each new shape we will encounter, we will compile a tvm kernel at runtime, and invoke it.

@wweic @jroesch @junrushao1994 @icemelon9 @vinx13 please review.

The `VirtualMachine` object currently contains both bytecode related information (e.g. constant pool, primitive names, etc) and VM specific data (e.g. pc, ip etc) which looks very heavy. It also makes serialization and deserialization work at the VM level although many of the VM internal data are not needed.

This PR extracts the bytecode and library related data out of the virtual machine and creates a separate vm Executable structure to hold such information. Therefore, VM becomes a thin runtime that operates on the executable. The VM compiler, serializer, and deserializer therefore only need to work on the Executable as well. For example, VM compiler compiles a Relay program and produces an Executable instead of a Virtual Machine which contains many uninitialized states. Thanks @icemelon9 and @wweic for  suggestions.

